snippet.textDisplay: Even if they did come out and say "we're making a Wii U port," The Wii U wouldn't be able to handle the game regardless. Even if R* did port it on Wii U, there would be no 1080p, a major drop in framrate, and also Nintendo has awful multiplayer severs (I had a Wii, Super Smash Bros Brawl had garbage online play). GTA V can barely handle itself on PS3 and 360 already with the cloud servers on multiplayer, the texture pop ups, and the draw distance would decrease on Wii U.

If they want to be innovative with peripheral devices, they have to show us why they're interesting and get developers to see that and utilize them too.  It's not happening with the Wii U (because the Wii U isn't interesting), and it (largely) didn't happen with the Wii.

snippet.textDisplay: Nintendo has a ridiculous amount of money sitting in their bank. They need to start using it more, in a smart way. Getting 3rd party support is essential. Microsoft did exactly that back then by getting GTA IV, Final Fantasy XIII, Metal Gear Solid 4, etc. and it worked.

snippet.textDisplay: This could be a big title for Wii U if released for it. That said, the Wii U's biggest problem would still exist, it lacks the exclusives to draw people in as most will still wind up only getting the game for PS3/360, even if it were announced for PS4, they'd still get it on PS3. PS3 I remember had the same problem for quite awhile, everyone still insisted on getting everything for PS2. We're slowly but surely becoming accustomed to what we have and not needing to go much further.

snippet.textDisplay: The Epsilon Program is a fictional religious cult in the GTA games. It was first used as a teaser site for GTA San Andreas, so it makes sense now that it's back in action to tease GTA V (which returns to San Andreas). They released a screensaver today along with a simple but surprisingly relaxing theme. I'm very excited for this game. Nintendo should do﻿ everything in its power to get this game on the Wii U and announce it during E3.
